Agent has instructed on setting up a Docker Compose server with Nginx, Let's Encrypt Certbot, virtual hosts, PHP 8.1, and MariaDB. The setup involves creating a directory structure and configuring several files, including a `docker-compose.yml`, `nginx/conf.d/default.conf.template`, and managing SSL certificates in the `nginx/ssl` directory. 

The user requested more details about the file structure under the `ssl` directory and the content of the `default.conf.template`. The `ssl` directory will hold SSL certificates and keys generated by Certbot, typically structured as follows:
- `cert.pem`: Contains the certificate.
- `chain.pem`: Contains the intermediate certificates.
- `fullchain.pem`: Contains both the certificate and the chain.
- `privkey.pem`: Contains the private key.

The `default.conf.template` file serves as a template for Nginx configuration and might look like this:
```
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name ${NGINX_HOST};
    return 301 https://${NGINX_HOST}$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name ${NGINX_HOST};

    ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/privkey.pem;

    location / {
        root /app;
        index index.php index.html index.htm;
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        fastcgi_pass php:9000;
        fastcgi_index index.php;
        fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
        include fastcgi_params;
    }
}
```

This template ensures proper redirection from HTTP to HTTPS and sets up PHP processing with Nginx.

